She was Aspirin, and she was always there, waiting. Waiting to make the world a little brighter, a little quieter, a little more bearable. And in her waiting, there was a kind of hope. A hope that the world could be better, that people could be kinder, that life could be a little less frantic. It was a hope that she carried with her, like a secret, like a promise. And it was this hope, more than anything else, that made everyone call her Aspirin. Because in her presence, you couldn't help but aspire. You couldn't help but feel that maybe, just maybe, things could be different. And that, in itself, was a kind of miracle. [end of text]


